LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2010"

\end_inset

.
 Six Victorian weather stations were selected for this analysis—shown in
 the appendix—.
 These stations provide the best available information for the computation
 of this index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2010"

\end_inset

.
 Seasonal fire weather in Victoria was also estimated using reanalysis data.
 Using the 20CR and HADISST data allowed to extend the calculations to the
 first half of the 20
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century.
 Climate data was also used to compute climate indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Climate indices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This investigation also explored the influence of several climate modes
 of variability over bushfires in Victoria.
 The El Niño Southern Oscillation (ENSO), Indean Ocean Dipole (IOD) and
 Southern Annular Mode (SAM) are among the most important for this region
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gong1999,Williams2001,Cai2009,Risbey2009b,Ho2011,Ummenhofer2011,White2013"

\end_inset

.
 Seasonal weather composites suggested a strong influence of ENSO over bushfire
 occurrences in Victoria.
 Thus, the analysis has a higher emphasis over this driver.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis used three ENSO indices, and one index for the IOD and SAM
 respectively.
 The Southern Oscillation Index (SOI), NINO3.4 and NINO1+2.
 The Dipole Mode Index (DMI) and Antartic Oscillation (AAO) revealed the
 relationships with IOD and SAM respectively.
 The analysis used climate indices data from several institutions: Australian
 Bureau of Meteorology (SOI), National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
 (NINO3.4, AAO), Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology (DMI).
 The climatologies used in the calculation of these indices were were 1951-2000
 (NINO3.4.), 1958-2010 (DMI), and 1979-2000 (AAO).
 The NINO1+2 index was computed using the HADISST data.
 The climatology for this index was 1911-2011 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The investigation of fire weather variability and forecasting skill in Victoria
 required four analyses: validation of bushfire activity data, computation
 of the McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index, formulation of the Victorian
 Seasonal Bushfire Index, and calculation of linear correlations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Validation of bushfire activity data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A comparison of the two bushfire datasets available—DELWP and Peril Aus—was
 necessary to confirm their consistency.
 Chapter 4 describes the details of this process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Computation of the McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The investigation used the FFDI to explore seasonal fire weather in Victoria.
 This index is commoly used in Australia to assess fire behaviour 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2010"

\end_inset

.
 The computation of the FFDI requires meteorological data reported on individual
 weather stations.
 The regional average of each FFDI variable was used to compute values for
 Victoria.
 On the other hand, averaging the gridded reanalysis data over Victoria
 yielded regional values for the computation of the index.
 The 20CR and WS data comprise daily values.
 However, this investigation aimed to analyse fire weather with a seasonal
 perspective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis used two seasonal metrics of FFDI.
 The first metric was the seasonal sum of daily FFDI values.
 The second metric was the number of days in a season that an FFDI exceeds
 a value of 25.
 In both cases, the seasons considered were SON and DJF.
 Additionally, a comparison of reanalysis and weather station data revealed
 the need for bias correction.
 Probability density functions (PDFs) and seasonal time series allowed to
 make these comparisons between the two types of data.
 The discussion section 
