\begin_layout Section
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This investigation explored seasonal fire weather variability in Victoria.
 Seasonal metrics of the McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index quantified bushfire
 danger using meteorological data.
 This chapter also proposed an alternative index: the “Victorian Seasonal
 Bushfire Index” (VSBI).
 The VSBI aggregates normalized seasonal averages of bushfire weather variables.
 The computation of the two indices used weather station and bias-corrected
 reanalysis data.
 Linear scaling techniques were used to bias-correct these data.
 Additionally, the chapter explores the relationship between bushfire activity,
 fire weather, climate modes of variability and meteorological variables.
 The relationship was analysed computing linear correlations for several
 variables in spring, summer and from spring to summer.
 This analysis investigated fire weather and activity prediction skills.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The seasonal fire weather variability shows an increasing trend during the
 period 1961-2010.
 This trend is consistent using weather station and reanalysis data.
 The trend is also consistent using different seasonal metrics of the FFDI.
 On the other hand, the VSBI shows a strong correlation with seasonal metrics
 of the FFDI in summer.
 VSBI in spring also shows moderate and statistically significant correlations
 with FFDI.
 VSBI and bushfire activity in summer are moderately correlated.
 However, relative humidity showed a stronger predictive skill than the
 VSBI itself—or FFDI—.
 This result implies that the linear assumption in the formulation of the
 VSBI does not increase its capability to represent—and predict—fire weather.
 Nevertheless, it seems that the availability of water content in the environmen
t is the most robust predictor of fire weather and activity in Victoria.
 Therefore, the development of a simple index to evaluate and forecast fire
 weather and activity in Victoria could be refined focusing on this variable
 and associated parameters (e.g.
 soil moisture).
 
\end_layout

